    <div class="content-panel">
      <h2 class="section-title section-title-glow">Online career coaching vs. in-person coaching</h2>
      <p>The core difference is access and flexibility, not quality. The best career coaches in the country are not located in every city. Online coaching gives you access to expertise that would not be available locally.</p>
      <p>Practically: mock interviews, resume reviews, LinkedIn audits, and salary negotiation coaching are all as effective — often more effective — in a virtual format. You can record sessions, revisit coaching materials, and access support at the moment you need it rather than waiting for the next in-person appointment.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="content-panel">
      <h2 class="section-title section-title-glow">Who online career coaching works best for</h2>
      <ul class="checklist">
        <li>Professionals in cities with limited access to specialized coaching talent</li>
        <li>Remote workers already comfortable operating in distributed environments</li>
        <li>Professionals targeting remote jobs — the job search is itself remote-first, so the coaching should be too</li>
        <li>Professionals with demanding schedules who need flexibility in session timing</li>
        <li>Professionals targeting roles in multiple markets simultaneously (local + remote)</li>
        <li>Anyone who has tried local coaching and found the expertise too general</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

